description:
I was able to launch a simulation with the mass action solver and managed to generate a trajectory in just over 1.07 seconds... If you read the description and haven't a clue what the 1st sentence means, and continue to find the entire description had no discernible meaning, still give it a go, and find when you try to open something, there's a directory called "examples" in there, where you can find a few example models... but .. then, what...? can't double-click one of them or don't think of trying, conclude there are no models and complain about that in your "review"..? Or was it that (didn't check) the models I tried were in Cain format, so you could just "open" them, but you wanted ones that you had to select "import" instead of "open"?
This may well be an educational tool, I have little idea. One probably needs to have a good idea what the description means, at least - to determine that.. which I don't. But don't blame the software because you have no clue what it is or does. It looks like it does stuff like it says, but I didn't like chemistry enough to take enough of it to get to a point where this stuff has more than a mere hint of meaning.
summary: Looks ok, probably does what it says it does
